{"id":"1801.07483","submitter":"Jules Guioth","authors":"Jules Guioth, \\'Eric Bertin","title":"Large deviations and chemical potential in bulk-driven systems in\n  contact","comments":"7 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1209/0295-5075/123/10002","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study whether the stationary state of two bulk-driven systems slowly\nexchanging particles can be described by the equality of suitably defined\nnonequilibrium chemical potentials. Our main result is that in a weak contact\nlimit, chemical potentials can be defined when the dynamics of particle\nexchange takes a factorized form with respect to the two systems, and satisfies\na macroscopic detailed balance property at large deviation level. The chemical\npotentials of systems in contact generically differ from the nonequilibrium\nchemical potentials of isolated systems, and do not satisfy an equation of\nstate. Yet, classes of systems satisfying the zeroth law of thermodynamics can\nbe defined in a natural way. These results are illustrated on a driven lattice\nparticle model and on an active particle model. The case when a chemical\npotential cannot be defined also has interesting consequences, like a\nnon-standard form of the grand-canonical ensemble.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 23 Jan 2018 11:08:30 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 26 Mar 2018 11:53:31 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Fri, 13 Jul 2018 09:02:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-08-29"}
